    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>fibrous obliterans.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The  appendiceal  lumen  is obliterated by fibroadipose tissue with focal lymphocytic  infiltration. No suppurative inflammation is seen.</div><div>    </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>APP_Periappendicitis</title>
    <created>20180703T065103Z</created>
    <updated>20260109T053654Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Periappendicitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The serosa is coated by fibrinopurulent exudate. There is no significant mural or luminal inflammation. It may indicate other intraabdominal pathology. Clinical correlation is suggested.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>APP_ruptured</title>
    <created>20170620T082311Z</created>
    <updated>20250417T054530Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Appendix, appendectomy --- Acute appendicitis, ruptured.</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The appendix measures __ cm in length, __ cm in diameter. The serosal</div><div>surface is markedly congested, rough, and coated with fibrinopurulent material.</div><div>A rupture hole measuring 0.1 - 0.2 cm is noted. The lumen contains pus.</div><div><br/></div><div>Representative sections are submitted in one cassette.</div><div><br/></div><div>Acute appendicitis, ruptured.</div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The appendiceal wall is partially necrotic with loss of its architecture. The PMN infiltration is diffuse and extensive, involving the entire thickness of the wall. The serosa is coated with fibrinopurulent exudate.        </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>APP_ruptured_right hemi</title>
    <created>20250417T054551Z</created>
    <updated>20250417T054925Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Appendix, needlescopic right hemicolectomy --- </div><div>Acute appendicitis, ruptured.</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Received is a right hemicolectomy specimen including</div><div>terminal ileum (_ cm in length and _ cm in circumference),</div><div>ascending colon (_ cm in length and _ cm in circumference),</div><div>and appendix (_ cm in length and _ cm in diameter).</div><div>The external surface of the appendix is coated with purulent exudates.</div><div><br/></div><div>Representative sections are taken and labeled as follows:</div><div>A1: Bilateral margins</div><div>A2¡VA3: Appendix</div><div>A4:</div><div>A5: Other area</div><div>A6: Pericolonic tissue</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The appendiceal wall is partially necrotic with loss of its architecture. The PMN infiltration is diffuse and extensive, involving the entire thickness of the wall. The serosa is coated with fibrinopurulent exudate.</div><div>A diverticulus revealing chronic inflammatory infiltrate near the base is seen.</div><div>Five lymph nodes seen show preserved nodal architecture. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>APPENDIX _ Form</title>
    <created>20260428T142723Z</created>
    <updated>20260428T143908Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic Type: Adenocarcinoma ___ Mucinous adenocarcinoma__ Signet-ring cell carcinom__ Goblet cell adenocarcinoma __Free texting </div><div>Tumor Size: Greatest dimension: ___ cm.</div><div>Histologic Grade: <span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">___ G1, well differentiated___ G2, moderately differentiated___ G3, poorly differentiated</span></div><div>Tumor Deposits:___ Not identified___ Present</div><div>Tumor Extension: 
 ___ Tumor invades lamina propria or muscularis mucosa
___ Acellular mucin invades submucosa
___ Tumor invades submucosa
___ Acellular mucin invades muscularis propria
___ Tumor invades muscularis propria
___ Acellular mucin invades subserosa or mesoappendix but does not extend to serosal surface
___ Tumor invades through muscularis propria into subserosa or mesoappendix but does not extend to
serosal surface
___ Acellular mucin invades visceral peritoneum (serosa)
___ Tumor invades visceral peritoneum (serosa)
___ Tumor directly invades adjacent organ(s) or structure</div><div>註解說明欄位: Acellular mucin or mucinous epithelium that extends into the subserosa or serosa should be classified as T3 or T4a, respectively</div><div>Margin: ___Cannot be evaluated  ___Involved by tumor cells _Presence with acellular mucin _Uninvolved, _ mm in distance.</div><div>Lymphovascular Invasion: Not identified _Present</div><div>Perineural Invasion: Not identified _Present</div><div>Regional Lymph Nodes: Not assessed</div><div>  Extranodal extension: Not applicable.</div><div>Additional Pathologic Findings: _____</div><div>pTNM: pT_N_ (AJCC 9th Edition).</div><div>TNM descriptors: <span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">___ Not applicable ___ y (post-neoadjuvant therapy) __ r (recurrence)</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Note:</div><div>This case is diagnosed by two doctors with peer review.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>At least intramucosal adenocarcinoma (see description)</title>
    <created>20180910T062651Z</created>
    <updated>20230705T074321Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>At least intramucosal adenocarcinoma (see description)</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows superficial sampling of colonic mucosal tissue composed of tubuloglandular structures that are lined by tall columnar epithelium exhibiting high-grade dysplasia with architectural complexity. Lamina propria invasion is noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>The overall features suggest an adenocarcinoma with invasion into lamina propria at least. The sample doesnt contain submucosal tissue for evaluation. Underlying invasion cannot be excluded due to superficial sampling of this tissue. Clinical correlation is suggested.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: No submucosal tissue is present for proper evaluation of invasion depth. Underlying submucosal invasion cannot be excluded.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20181129T031819Z</created>
    <updated>20181129T031925Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Autoimmune metaplastic atrophic gastritis/pernicious anemia pattern</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: The patient is at risk for pernicious anemia. Correlation with anti-parietal and anti-intrinsic factor antibodies as well as vitamin B12 levels is recommended. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BARRETT c/w Barrett&apos;s esophagus, esophagocardiac junction</title>
    <created>20160718T071138Z</created>
    <updated>20251219T031444Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>R/O Barrett's esophagus    </div><div><br/></div><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Esophagogastric junction, endoscopic biopsy --- <span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Consistent with Barrett's esophagus.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>Section shows juxtaposed squamous and gastric-type mucosa with intestinal metaplasia and chronic inflammatory infiltrate in the lamina propria.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BARRETT c/w Barrett&apos;s esophagus, esophagocardiac junction (no IM)</title>
    <created>20171214T075132Z</created>
    <updated>20230830T045138Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows esophageal squamous mucosa and cardiac</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">type mucosa with acute and chronic inflammatory infiltrate in the lamina propria.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Although no intestinal metaplasia is seen, the picture</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">can be consistent with Barrett's</span> <span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">esophagus. Please correlate with endoscopic finding.</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BARRETT c/w Barrett&apos;s esophagus, esophagocardiac junction (有IM)</title>
    <created>20171214T073828Z</created>
    <updated>20250219T071807Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>R/O Barrett's esophagus    </div><div><br/></div><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Esophagogastric junction, endoscopic biopsy --- <span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Consistent with Barrett's esophagus.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows esophageal squamous mucosa and cardiac </span>type mucosa with chronic inflammatory infiltrate. Intestinal metaplasia is focally seen. The picture can be consistent with Barrett's <span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">esophagus</span>.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BRAF (VE1) positive report</title>
    <created>20170322T002349Z</created>
    <updated>20170322T002407Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>COMMENT: BRAF (VE1) immunohistochemistry is strongly concordant with BRAF V600E</div><div>mutation. The presence of a BRAF V600E mutation suggests that the tumor is sporadic</div><div>and germline evaluation is probably not indicated.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>C/W UC</title>
    <created>20161213T004150Z</created>
    <updated>20230831T053516Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>consistent with ulcerative colitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows colonic mucosal tissue with focal ulceration and a heavy infiltrate of mixed inflammatory cells including many eosinophils in the lamina propria. Lymphoid follicles formation is also observed. Cryptitis and crypt abscess are seen. These findings are not pathognomonic but consistent with ulcerative colitis. No viral inclusions are demonstrated by anti-CMV immunostain.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CAG HP (CK) [caghpck]</title>
    <created>20170103T005030Z</created>
    <updated>20240923T051807Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>chronic active gastritis with Helicobacter pylori infection.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric tissue with abundant infiltrate of</div><div>mixed inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Helicobacter</div><div>pylori microorganisms are identified in the gastric pits.</div><div>No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div>    </div><div>Ancillary studies:</div><div>Immunohistochemical stain: AE1/AE3.</div><div style="padding-left:40px;">                </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CAG HP (CK/Giemsa) [caghpgiemsack]</title>
    <created>20211223T083332Z</created>
    <updated>20250220T015342Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>chronic active gastritis with Helicobacter pylori infection.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric tissue with infiltrate of acute and chronic inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Some Helicobacter pylori microorganisms are highlighted by Giemsa stain.</div><div>No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div><div>Ancillary studies:</div><div>1. Special stain: Giemsa stain</div><div>2. Immunohistochemical stain: AE1/AE3.    </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CAG HP (Giemsa) [caghpgiemsa]</title>
    <created>20240923T051644Z</created>
    <updated>20240929T150007Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>chronic active gastritis with Helicobacter pylori infection. </div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric tissue with infiltrate of acute and chronic inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Some Helicobacter pylori microorganisms are highlighted by Giemsa stain. </div><div><br/></div><div>Ancillary studies:</div><div>Special stain: Giemsa stain.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CAG HP IM low-grade</title>
    <created>20240216T064834Z</created>
    <updated>20240216T064946Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>-- chronic active gastritis with Helicobacter pylori </div><div>   infection.</div><div>-- intestinal metaplasia and low-grade dysplasia</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric tissue with infiltrate of</div><div>mixed inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Helicobacter</div><div>pylori microorganisms are identified in the gastric pits.</div><div>Intestinal metaplasia with low-grade dysplasia is seen, characterized by irregularity in shape with slight increase of the nucleo-cytoplasmic ratio, depletion of mucin. </div><div>No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div><div>Ancillary studies:</div><div>Immunohistochemical stain: AE1/AE3.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
