      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Hyperplastic polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows hyperplastic squamous and foveolar epithelium</div><div>with areas showing superficial erosion and granulation</div><div>tissue which is inflammed and infiltrated by lymphoplasma</div><div>cells including eosinophils.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Esophagus- moderate dysplasia</title>
    <created>20210701T050523Z</created>
    <updated>20251029T031441Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>High-grade squamous dysplasia. (moderate dysplasia)</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows squamous mucosal tissue revealing focal high-grade dysplasia characterized by involvement of more than half of the epithelium by dysplastic cells.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, p40 and Ki-67 highlights the dysplastic cells without evidence of invasion.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>External hemorrhoid EH</title>
