  <note>
    <title>Focal adenomatous change, ampulla of Vater, biopsy</title>
    <created>20160726T083625Z</created>
    <updated>20230907T031515Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Focal adenomatous change.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The mucosal tissue of ampulla vater is focally replaced by dysplastic epithelium revealing pseudostratified and hyperchromatic nuclei. There are chronic inflammatory infiltrate in the lamina propria. No stromal invasion is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Foveolar-type adenoma.</title>
    <created>20211005T073940Z</created>
    <updated>20250613T055209Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><h3 style="--en-nodeId:0e1aebe3-5723-4fee-b13d-39908cd7885d;"><b><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Foveolar-type adenoma.</span></b></h3><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Section shows dysplastic columnar epithelium of foveolar type with stratified elongated nuclei. A distinctive apical cap opf neutral miucin is highlighted by PAS. </span></div><div>No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Gastric antral vascular ectasia (stomach)</title>
    <created>20170110T021838Z</created>
    <updated>20170110T021855Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>The gastric antral mucosa shows hyperplastic, tortuous foveolar epithelium with some dilated mucosal capillaries, focal thrombi, and fibromuscular proliferation.  Combined with clinical findings, the histologic features are compatible with gastric antral vascular ectasia. The duodenum and omentum are unremarkable. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>gastric dysplasia/low-grade dysplasia/foveolar-type</title>
    <created>20210218T071132Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T092126Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>low-grade dysplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows focal foveolar-type, low-grade dysplasia</div><div>of gastric mucosa, characterized by elongated nuclei located</div><div>at the base. No Helicobacter Pylori is demonstrated by</div><div>Giemsa stain.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) (form)</title>
    <created>20230906T092855Z</created>
    <updated>20250106T101758Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows spindle and epithelioid cells with faintly</div><div>eosinophilic cytoplasm, elongated nuclei and inconspicuous</div><div>nucleoli. Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are</div><div>positive for CD117, DOG1, CD34 but not desmin, and S100,</div><div>confirming the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Glycogenic acanthosis.</title>
    <created>20200618T090554Z</created>
    <updated>20200618T090739Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Glycogenic acanthosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows epithelial thickening by large squamous cells revealing clear cell change.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Goblet Cell-rich hyperplastic polyp [COL8]</title>
    <created>20181229T045730Z</created>
    <updated>20231020T060702Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Goblet cell-rich hyperplastic polyp</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Hyperplastic polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows crypts containing large number of goblets cells with superficial serration. <span>    </span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Hamartomatous polyp, stomach</title>
    <created>20161216T021209Z</created>
    <updated>20240626T022321Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>hamartomatous polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a polypoid lesion composed of hyperplastic foveolar epithelium with</div><div>focal intestinal metaplasia, and prominent fibromuscular proliferation as demonstrated</div><div>by SMA immunostain. A mixed infiltrate of chronic and acute inflammatory cells in the</div><div>lamina propria is also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>hamartomatous polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>It shows finely arborizing branches of smooth muscle covered by normal but disorganized mucosa, without prominent inflammation.</div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the smooth muscle is highlighted by desmin.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Hemorrhoid</title>
    <created>20170420T065241Z</created>
    <updated>20250827T025302Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Consistent with mixed hemorrhoid.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>The section reveals anal tissue in which the underlying stroma are occupied by variably dilated or congested vessels filled with RBCs. Although no rectal mucosal tissue is seen, it can be consistent with mixed hemorrhoid.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Herpes esophagitis</title>
    <created>20170217T055746Z</created>
    <updated>20170217T055806Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>The esophageal mucosal tissues show ulceration with intraepithelial neutrophilic infiltration and reactive epithelial atypia. Separate necrotic exudates are also seen</div><div>admixed with the squamous cells revealing nuclear changes of nuclear moulding, chromatin margination and multinucleation, consistent with Herpes esophagitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>The GMS and PAS stains are negative for fungal hyphae. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>ADDENDUM REPORT (ISSUED on 2015/03/13)</div><div>Immunostaining for anti-CMV performed per request by the clinician is negative. The</div><div>histologic findings are characteristics for Herpes simplex esophagitis.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Heterotopic gastric mucosa, duodenum</title>
    <created>20160726T080948Z</created>
    <updated>20230616T032408Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Heterotopic gastric mucosa.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows duodenal tissue focally replaced by gastric</div><div>foveolar epithelial cells with fundic glands in the lamina</div><div>propria. No evidence of malignancy is seen.</div><div>            <span>    </span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>High-grade dysplasia at least.</title>
    <created>20260203T024308Z</created>
    <updated>20260203T024420Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>High-grade dysplasia at least.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows tubuloglandular structures lined by dysplastic epithelium exhibiting high-grade dysplasia. Underlying invasiveness cannot be excluded.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>High-grade dysplasia(stomach)</title>
    <created>20170116T003613Z</created>
    <updated>20250305T033038Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric mucosal fragments revealing intestinal metaplasia and high-grade</div><div>dysplasia characterized by architectural complexity.</div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">No Helicobacter Pylori is seen. </span></span></div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, AE1/AE3 highlights the dysplastic glands in cribriform pattern.</div><div><br/></div><div><b><a href="https://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/esophagusadenocarcinomaintramucosal.html" rev="en_rl_none"><span style="color:rgb(5, 79, 150);">Intramucosal adenocarcinoma</span></a><span style="color:rgb(5, 79, 150);"> Criteria</span></b></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>High-grade glandular dysplasia, associated with Barrett esophagus.</title>
    <created>20251217T022806Z</created>
    <updated>20251217T022828Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Esophago-cardiac junction, endoscopic biopsy ---</div><div>High-grade glandular dysplasia, associated with Barrett esophagus.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows juxtaposed squamous and gastric type mucosal</div><div>tissue revealing focal high-grade glandular dysplasia</div><div>associated with intestinal metaplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, AE1/AE3 highlights the dysplastic</div><div>glands without evidence of invasion. P53 is increased.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>high-grade glandular dysplasia.</title>
    <created>20181211T034145Z</created>
    <updated>20200207T090327Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>high-grade glandular dysplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric-type mucosal tissue revealing focal high-grade dysplasia characterized by architectural complexity, and increased N:C ratio.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, AE1/AE3 highlights the dysplastic glands without evidence of invasion.</div><div><span style="font-size: 12px; font-family: gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;">No Helicobacter Pylori is seen. </span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Hyperplastic polyp (stomach) [stoHP]</title>
    <created>20171206T064859Z</created>
    <updated>20230606T075439Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="line-height: 1.45;">hyperplastic polyp.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows elongation, turtousity and dilatation of the gastric foveola, associated with stromal edema and </span><span style="line-height: 1.45;">inflammatory infiltration.</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px; font-family: gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;">No Helicobacter Pylori is seen.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>                            </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Hyperplastic polyp with Helicobacter pylori infection</title>
    <created>20161222T062104Z</created>
    <updated>20161222T062125Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>

<div style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: small; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Sections show a picture of hyperplastic polyp with Helicobacter pylori microorganisms in the gastric pits. No malignancy is observed.</div></div><div><br/>

</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IBD checklist</title>
    <created>20240515T130241Z</created>
    <updated>20241213T030917Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>2024.9更新 twiap</div><div><br/></div><ul><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Architectural distortion: not identified/mild/moderate/severe</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Nancy index:</span></div></li></ul><div>  absence of significant histological disease (grade 0)</div><div>  chronic inflammatory infiltrate with no acute inflammatory infiltrate (grade 1)</div><div>  mildly active disease (grade 2)</div><div>  moderately active disease (grade 3)</div><div>  severely active disease (grade 4)</div><ul><li><div>Granuloma: not identified/present in section____.</div></li><li><div>Paneth metaplasia in distal colon (splenic flexure and beyond): not identified/present in section____.</div></li><li><div>Pyloric metaplasia: not identified/present in section____.</div></li><li><div>Basal plasmacytosis: not identified/present in section____.</div></li><li><div> Neutrophilic infiltrate:  lamina propria   cryptitis   microabscess</div></li><li><div>Dysplasia: not identified/indefinite for dysplasia/present in section____</div></li></ul><div style="padding-left:40px;">(1) Conventional dysplasia: low-grade/high-grade </div><div style="padding-left:40px;">(2) Nonconventional dysplasia: type: hypermucinous/goblet cell deficient/crypt <span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">cell dysplasia/traditional serrated adenoma (TSA)-like/sessile serrated lesion (SSL)-like/serrated dysplasia, no otherwise specified. </span></div><ul><li><div>Fissuring ulcer: not identified/present in section____.</div></li><li><div>Ancillary studies:</div></li></ul><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">  No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.     </span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">  No viral inclusion is demonstrated by anti-CMV immunostain.    </span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="--en-markholder:true;"><br/></span></span></span></div><div>Overall assessment: (optional)</div><ul><ul><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Normal or nearly normal intestinal tissue </span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Mild non-specific chronic inflammation</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Quiescent colitis</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">More supportive of acute colitis</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">More supportive of ulcerative colitis</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">More supportive of Crohn’s disease</span></div></li><li><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Supportive of inflammatory bowel disease but further subclassification can't be done</span></div></li></ul></ul><div style="padding-left:40px;"><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span style="--en-markholder:true;"><br/></span></span></div><div><br/></div><div>Comment:</div><ol><li><div>The diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease cannot be made by histology alone. Please correlate with clinical presentation.</div></li><li><div>The absence of inflammation or only mild inflammation can be due to sampling of uninflammatory sites or treatment and cannot be used against the diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease.</div></li></ol><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><hr/><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Explanatory Note:</span></div><ol><li><div>Please make the diagnosis and rule out other disease (such as amebiasis, lymphoma, etc.) before grading the lesions.  </div></li><li><div>Nancy Index: </div></li><ol><li><div>Grade 0: No or only mild increase in chronic inflammatory cells</div></li><li><div>Grade 1: Moderate or severe increase in chronic inﬂammatory cells (lymphocytes, plasma cells, and eosinophils) deﬁned as presence of an increase in chronic inﬂammatory cells that is easily apparent.</div></li><li><div>Grade 2: Mild increase in neutrophils deﬁned as few or rare neutrophils in lamina propria or in the epithelium that are difﬁcult to see</div></li><li><div>Grade 3: Moderate or severe increase neutrophils deﬁned as presence of multiple clusters of neutrophils in lamina propria and/or in epithelium that are easily apparent</div></li><li><div>Grade 4: Ulcers or erosions deﬁned as loss of colonic crypts replaced with “immature” granulation tissue (disorganized blood vessels with extravasated neutrophils) or the presence of ﬁbrinopurulent exudate</div></li></ol><li><div>CMV immunostaining is suggested for all cases with ulceration and treatment refractory colitis</div></li><ol><li><div>Some antibody clones (such as the clone used in Ventana machine) showed non-specific cytoplasmic granular staining in neutrophils. Please only interpretate the cells with strong positive nuclear staining as positive. </div></li><li><div><span style="--en-highlight:yellow;background-color: #ffef9e;">CMV immunostaining should be graded as low grade (&lt;=4 positive cells per piece of tissue) or high grade (>5 positive cells in at least one piece of tissue)</span></div></li></ol><li><div><span style="--en-highlight:yellow;background-color: #ffef9e;">SATB2 is lost in 40% of IBD-associated dysplasia </span>but not loss in regenerative colonic mucosa. Hence, SATB2 immunostaining is suggested for cases with indefinite for dysplasia.</div></li><li><div>Lymphoid aggregate and lymphoid follicle formation are normal finding for terminal ileum specimen. Should not diagnose as inflammatory tissue only based on this finding. </div></li><li><div>Histologic remission is defined as Nancy grade 0 or 1 and is used as the criteria for treatment end point. </div></li><li><div>The American College of Gastroenterology and American Gastroenterology Association suggest that the presence or absence of dysplasia is confirmed by at least one pathologist who is skilled in GI pathology or who has broad experience with dysplasia in UC. </div></li></ol><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);"> </span></div><en-media hash="2c76d764cf1892a5c76330794a0f958e" type="image/png" style="--en-naturalWidth:1380; --en-naturalHeight:736;" /><div><br/></div><div><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">(A) Ulceration of colonic mucosa with inflamed granulation tissue corresponding to </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 4</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index (HES ×200). (B) Ulceration of colonic mucosa with neutrophils in fibrin corresponding to </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 4</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index (HES ×200). (C) Presence of multiple clusters of neutrophils in lamina propria and/or in epithelium that are easily apparent. Acute inflammatory cells infiltrate is moderate to severe, corresponding to </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 3</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index. (HES ×200). (D) Presence of few or rare neutrophils in lamina propria or in the epithelium that are difficult to see. Acute inflammatory cells infiltrate is mild, corresponding to </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 2</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index (HES ×200). (E) Biopsy specimen showing no acute inflammatory cells infiltrate and presence of a moderate-to-severe increase in chronic inflammatory cells number corresponding to </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 1</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index (HES ×200). (F) Biopsy specimen showing a mild increase in chronic inflammatory cell number. In this case, it defines a </span><i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">grade 0</span></i><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);"> of the Nancy index (HES ×200). HES, hematoxylin-eosin-saffron.</span></div><div><span style="color:rgb(38, 38, 38);">Marchal-Bressenot et al. Gut, 2016</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
    <resource>
