  <note>
    <title>Inflamed Hyperplastic Polyp [COL8]</title>
    <created>20181229T045559Z</created>
    <updated>20181229T045719Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>hyperplastic polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows an hyperplastic polyp with intraepithelial and lamina propria inflammation.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180524T141430Z</created>
    <updated>20190227T044236Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inflammatory cloacogenic polyp</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The polyp is lined by both squamous and columnar mucosa, displaying a tubulovillous growth pattern with abundant fibromuscular stroma. Superficial ulceration with granulation tissue is seen.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Inflammatory fibroid polyp.</title>
    <created>20191015T072827Z</created>
    <updated>20240318T032130Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inflammatory fibroid polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows sumucosal proliferation of lesional cells centered around vessels. Inflammatory cells including lymphocytes and eosinophils are seen in the background.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the lesional cells are positive for CD34 but not CD117, S100, desmin, or EMA, consistent with the diagnosis.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Inflammatory polyp</title>
    <created>20170216T050506Z</created>
    <updated>20230713T063429Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inflammatory polyp.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The polyp is composed of variably-sized glands surrounded by edematous stroma, in which some inflammatory cell infiltration is noted.    </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Inflammatory polyp [esophagus]</title>
    <created>20230803T060040Z</created>
    <updated>20241210T030154Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Inflammatory polyp.</div><div>Microscopic description: </div><div>Section shows polypoid lesion lined by squamous epithelium with hyperplasia and downward growth. The stroma is edematous with mixed inflammatory infiltrate and capillary proliferation. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>insufficient</title>
    <created>20200629T095809Z</created>
    <updated>20250714T025449Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Colon, _____, colonoscopic polypectomy ---</div><div>Insufficient specimen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross description:</div><div>The specimen consists of a tiny piece of tissue measuring &lt;0.1x0.1x0.1 cm.</div><div>All for section.</div><div><br/></div><div>Insufficient specimen.</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows inadequate specimen which contains few colonic</div><div>epithelium only and cannot make a diagnosis.</div><div>    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Internal hemorrhoid [IH]</title>
    <created>20170420T065223Z</created>
    <updated>20230713T064357Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Internal hemorrhoid</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The section reveals rectal tissue in which the underlying stroma are occupied</div><div>by variably dilated or congested vessels filled with RBCs.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intestinal pseudo-obstruction, constipation, inertia</title>
    <created>20170601T054852Z</created>
    <updated>20250318T050843Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Colon, total abdominal colectomy ---</div><div>consistent with intestinal pseudo-obstruction.</div><div>Vascular congestion and fibrosis, clinically colonic inertia.</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Received is a total colectomy specimen including ileum (__ cm in length, __ cm in diameter), appendix (__ cm in length, __ cm in diameter), and colon (__ cm in length, __ cm in circumference). The mucosa of colon is focally flattening with variable thickness of bowel wall. No tumor is seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Representative sections are taken and labeled as follows:</div><div>A1: bilateral margins</div><div>A2: appendix</div><div>A3: ileocecal valve</div><div>A4-A8 colon</div><div>A9: pericolonic fat    </div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The colonic tissue shows variable thickness of muscularis propria with degenerative</div><div>change of myocytes, accompanied by delicate interstitial fibrosis in the muscularis</div><div>propria, especially the inner circular layer which is highlighted by Masson Trichrome</div><div>stain. Vascular congestion of bowel wall and focal submucosal fibrosis are also seen. Ganglion cells are present throughout</div><div>the colonic segments that were sampled. No evidence of inflammation or infection is</div><div>seen. The appendix is unremarkable.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, <span style="color:rgb(251, 95, 44);">S100 </span>stain demonstrates the neural plexuses without remarkable</div><div>changes. <span style="color:rgb(251, 95, 44);">CD117 </span>highlights the interstitial cells of Cajal. <span style="color:rgb(251, 95, 44);">SMA </span>and <span style="color:rgb(251, 95, 44);">desmin </span>show no</div><div>obvious decreased staining in the muscular layer. Staining for Congo red is negative,</div><div>excluding amyloidosis. No inclusion or microorganism is demonstrated by PAS stain.</div><div><br/></div><div>The overall features suggest motility disorder which can be primary or secondary to</div><div>systemic conditions such as diabetes mellitus, scleroderma or drug injury etc.</div><div>Clinical correlation is recommended.</div><hr/><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The colonic tissue shows variable thickness of muscularis propria with vascular congestion of bowel wall. Ganglion cells are present throughout the colonic segments that were sampled. No evidence of inflammation or infection is</div><div>seen. The appendix is unremarkable.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>intestinal-type adenoma. [duodenum,small intestine, ampulla]</title>
    <created>20210316T044122Z</created>
    <updated>20250709T040149Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Intestinal-type adenoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows crowded tubuloglandular structures that are lined by tall columnar epithelium in which individual cells exhibit mild dysplasia. Paneth and goblet cells are intermingled. No frank malignancy is noted.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intramucosal adenocarcinoma</title>
    <created>20171205T100040Z</created>
    <updated>20260324T025939Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <source>mobile.ipad</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Intramucosal adenocarcinoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows crowded tubuloglandular structures that are </span>lined by tall columnar epithelium. The lining epithelium exhibit high-grade dysplasia which shows rounded, heaped-up cells with open chromatin and prominent nucleoli, as well as architectural complexity. Lamina propria invasion is focally noted. The surgical margin is free. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: Intramucosal adenocarcinoma is biologically equivalent to high-grade dysplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>[We report intramucosal carcinoma in adenomas as such and always include a note stating that it is biologically equivalent to high-grade dysplasia (Tis) and that complete polypectomy should be curative. We report our findings this way in case additional sampling discloses deeper invasion.]</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Intramucosal adenocarcinoma [F] 12</title>
    <created>20170421T015929Z</created>
    <updated>20230831T032024Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>1. Tumor histological type: intramucosal adenocarcinoma</div><div>2. Tumor size:     cm</div><div>3. Histological grade: well differentiated</div><div>4. Invasion depth: invades the lamina propria (Tis)</div><div>5. Depth of submucosa invasion: not applicable</div><div>6. Angiolymphatic invasion: absent</div><div>7. Perineural invasion: absent</div><div>8. Margin: uninvolved</div><div>9. Immunohistochemical stain: SMA highlights the muscularis mucosae.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: Intramucosal adenocarcinoma is biologically equivalent to high-grade dysplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180817T060802Z</created>
    <updated>20180817T061051Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
