    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>iom</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>IPMN, pancrease</title>
    <created>20160808T004647Z</created>
    <updated>20160809T021706Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: small; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 1; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">The cystic tumor show intraductal proliferation of columnar mucin-producing cells, extending microscopically into the smaller pancreatic ducts beyond the grossly visible cystic tumor. There is focal low-grade dysplasia of the epithelium. No invasive component is identified. The pancreatic resection margin is __.</span>

</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Ischemic colitis</title>
    <created>20161102T053934Z</created>
    <updated>20250807T050654Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Consistent with ischemic colitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>It shows superficial mucosal erosion, atrophy of crypt and fibrosis in the lamina propria.</div><div><br/></div><div>consistent with ischemic colitis.</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows colonic tissues with active colitis, hemorrhage and vascular congestion in the lamina propria with focal epithelial necrosis. Mucopurulent exudates with sloughing ulcer are present. The findings are compatible with ischemic colitis. There is no granulomatous lesion or malignancy.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Consistent with ischemic colitis.</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows superficial epithelial erosion with preserved deep portion of the colonic crypts, accompanied by focal reactive atypia. Fibrosis and granulation tissue formation in the lamina propria are also discerned. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Kayexalate / resin</title>
    <created>20230523T072847Z</created>
    <updated>20230525T064235Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>-- Ulceration.</div><div>-- Kayexalate identified, See note</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The mucosal tissue reveals partial destruction of the mucosa</div><div>with infiltrate of acute and chronic inflammatory cells.</div><div>Necrotic debris are seen over the destructed surface.</div><div>No viral inclusion is demonstrated by anti-CMV immunostain.</div><div>Some bright purple crystals with fish scale appearance are</div><div>identified. These structures are black on AFB and are</div><div>also highlighted by PAS stain, consistent with Kayexalate.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: Kayexalate was associated with mucosal injury.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>LAMN</title>
    <created>20170503T060031Z</created>
    <updated>20231012T074002Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>The appendix show dilated lumen containing mucus with lining mucosa revealing areas of  villous hyperplasia with mild cellular atypia and also areas of attenuation of the mucosa, loss of submucosal lymphoid tissue and obliteration of muscularis mucosa.</div><div>Acelllular mucin pools in the wall, subserosal tissue and focal serosal surface are noted. No evidence of invasive carcinoma is seen. Five pericolic lymph nodes are identified and they are free of metastasis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is consistent with a low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm with  focal acellular mucin spread beyond serosa. The surgical margins are free of tumor.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic Type: Low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm</div><div>Tumor Size: Greatest dimension: ___ cm.</div><div>Histologic Grade: G1: Well differentiated</div><div>Tumor Extension:  . Acellular mucin or mucinous epithelium that extends into the subserosa or serosa should be classified as T3 or T4a, respectively</div><div>Margin: Cannot be evaluated </div><div>  Proximal Margin: Free of tumor, > 0.5 cm.</div><div>Lymphovascular Invasion: Not identified.</div><div>Tumor Deposits: Not identified.</div><div>Perineural Invasion: Not identified.</div><div>Regional Lymph Nodes: Not assessed</div><div>  Extranodal extension: Not applicable.</div><div>   pNX: Regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed</div><div>Additional Pathologic Findings: Ruptured acute suppurative appendicitis.</div><div>pTNM: pT4aNx (AJCC 8th Edition).</div><div>TNM descriptors: Not applicable.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note:</div><div>This case is diagnosed by two doctors with peer review.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Leiomyoma</title>
    <created>20170202T074126Z</created>
    <updated>20250929T024818Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Leiomyoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows colonic mucosal tissue with proliferative fascicles of spindle cells with brightly eosinophilic cytoplasm and blunt-ended nuclei, in association with muscularis mucosae. Neither increased mitotic activity nor cellular atypia is noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the spindle cells are positive for desmin but not CD34 or</div><div>CD117, consistent with smooth muscle differentiation.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>    </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Lymphangioma</title>
    <created>20170509T052153Z</created>
    <updated>20230726T023750Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Lymphangioma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows duodenal mucosal tissue with dilated lymphatic spaces in the submucosa</div><div>and focally in the lamina propria.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Melanosis coli.</title>
    <created>20180119T080048Z</created>
    <updated>20230525T081339Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>melanosis coli.</div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Section shows colonic mucosal tissue with aggregates of</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">macrophages filled with lipofusicin-like pigment (pseudomelanin) in the lamina propria, consistent with melanosis coli.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Meta Colorectal CA with CDX2 negative COMMENT</title>
    <created>20181029T022703Z</created>
    <updated>20230710T091105Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>COMMENT:</div><div>The overall features show metastatic adenocarcinoma with immunophenotypes (CK7+/CK20-/CDX2-) not typical for colorectal origin. However, a proportion of colorectal</div><div>adenocarcinoma can be CK20-negative or with loss of CDX2 expression. A diagnosis of metastatic adenocarcinoma of colorectal origin can be made after clinico-radiological</div><div>correlation for exclusion of other origin.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Metastatic adenocarcinoma, consistent with colorectal origin</title>
    <created>20251009T060008Z</created>
    <updated>20251009T060025Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Metastatic adenocarcinoma, consistent with colorectal origin.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>Section shows lung tissue infiltrated by complex tubuloglandular structures lined by neoplastic columnar cells with necrosis. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for CDX-2, consistent with metastatic adenocarcinoma of colorectal origin.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>MH Mixed hemorrhoid</title>
    <created>20170420T065149Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T061509Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Mixed hemorrhoid.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>The slide reveals both external anal and distal rectal mucosal tissues, both of which exhibit markedly congested or dilated vessels that are filled with RBCs.                             </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Microvesicular hyperplastic polyp [COL8] [MVHP]</title>
    <created>20180201T060311Z</created>
    <updated>20240328T043038Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="line-height: 1.45;">Section shows serrated crypts which are narrow and straight. The surface epithelium shows serration and is composed of a mixture of microvesicular and goblet cells. </span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Mild CI</title>
    <created>20180823T090447Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T064305Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
