      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>-- Ulcer with Helicobacter pylori infection.</div><div>-- Intestinal metaplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric mucosal tissue with focal ulceration and mixed inflammatory infiltrate in the lamina propria. Intestinal metaplasia is also seen. Some Helicobacter Pylori microorganisms are demonstrated by Giemsa stain. No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Ulcer, no CMV (colon) [COLulcer]</title>
    <created>20161205T070014Z</created>
    <updated>20250226T081904Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Ulceration.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>Section shows colonic mucosal tissue with ulceration, granulation tissue formation and mixed inflammatory infiltrate. No viral inclusion is <span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">highlighted by anti-CMV immunostain.</span></span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">No malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>There is no granuloma or cryptitis, crypt abscess identified.    </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ULCER00 no HP no fungus [stoulcer</title>
    <created>20180507T060016Z</created>
    <updated>20250224T022025Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>ulceration.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">The gastric tissue reveals partial destruction of the mucosa with infiltrate of acute and chronic inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Necrotic debris are seen over the destructed surface. </span></div><div>No Helicobacter pylori microorganisms are identified by Giemsa stain. No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3. No fungus is highlighted by PAS. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">Ancillary studies:</span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">1. Special stain: Giemsa stain, PAS.</span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">2. Immunohistochemical stain: AE1/AE3.    </span></span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Ulceration with cellular atypia</title>
    <created>20170322T012104Z</created>
    <updated>20250227T071139Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Ulceration with cellular atypia (see COMMENT)</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric tissue fragments revealing partial</div><div>destruction of the mucosa with marked infiltration by mixed</div><div>inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. Necrotic</div><div>debris is seen over the destructed surface as well as</div><div>separate fragments. No Helicobacter Pylori is seen. No</div><div>invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div><div>COMMENT:</div><div>Focal cellular atypia along the ulcer base is noted. This is</div><div>most likely due to the ulcer/inflammation. However, the</div><div>possibility of dysplasia cannot be excluded. Please</div><div>re-biopsy after the treatment of the ulcer.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Ulceration with cellular atypia (Esophagus)</title>
    <created>20251029T021946Z</created>
    <updated>20251029T022105Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Ulceration with cellular atypia (see COMMENT).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows juxtaposed squamous and gastric mucosal tissue</div><div>with ulceration and mixed inflammatory cells infiltrate. </div><div>No intestinal metaplasia is seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>COMMENT:</div><div>Focal cellular atypia of the squamous epithelium is noted along the ulcer base. p53 demonstrates a wild-type staining pattern, while Ki-67 is increased. These changes are most likely reactive, secondary to ulceration and inflammation; however, the possibility of dysplasia cannot be entirely excluded. Clinical follow-up and re-biopsy, if indicated, are recommended.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
